'''Jen-Hsun''' "'''Jensen'''" '''Huang'''{{efn|Huang consistently capitalizes the second syllable of his given name in legal documents.  For example, on April 5, 1993, he signed Nvidia's original articles of incorporation as Jen-Hsun Huang.<ref name="NVIDIA_Articles">{{cite web |last1=Huang |first1=Jen-Hsun |title=Articles of Incorporation of NVidia Corporation |url=https://bizfileonline.sos.ca.gov/api/report/GetImageByNum/034117059052077044090092010255252084026143162165 |website=bizfile online |publisher=California Secretary of State |access-date=October 11, 2024 |date=April 5, 1993}}</ref>}} ({{lang-zh|t=黃仁勳|poj=N̂g Jîn-hun|hp=Huáng Rénxūn}}; born February 17, 1963) is a Taiwanese and American <!-- Huang holds both Taiwanese and American citizenship with notability in both countries; per [[MOS:CONTEXTBIO]].  -->businessman, [[electrical engineer]], and philanthropist who is the president, co-founder, and [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) of [[Nvidia]], the world's largest [[semiconductor company]].<ref name=":0">{{cite news |last=Nimmo |first=Jamie |date=July 4, 2020 |title='It would be a tragedy if ARM did not move into the new era,' says Nvidia boss Jensen Huang |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/it-would-be-a-tragedy-if-arm-did-not-move-into-the-new-era-says-nvidia-boss-jensen-huang-7fp2qgxvv |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240323194415/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/it-would-be-a-tragedy-if-arm-did-not-move-into-the-new-era-says-nvidia-boss-jensen-huang-7fp2qgxvv |archive-date=March 23, 2024 |access-date=April 27, 2024 |work=[[The Sunday Times]]}}</ref> As of December 2024, ''[[Forbes]]'' estimated Huang's net worth at US$124.0 billion, making him the 10th wealthiest person in the world.<!-- Forbes's "Real Time Net Worth" of Jensen Huang is frequently updated, so when you update the net worth here, check that Forbes's web page was archived in Web Archive at this date, and update the archive date in the reference. --><ref name="Forbes">{{Cite web |date=December 23, 2024 |title=Jensen Huang: CEO & President, NVIDIA |url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/jensen-huang/ |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20241210021443/https://www.forbes.com/profile/jensen-huang/ |archive-date=2024-12-10 |access-date=23 December 2024 |website=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]}}</ref>

The son of [[Taiwanese Americans|Taiwanese American]] immigrants, Huang spent his childhood in Taiwan and Thailand before moving to the United States, where he was a student in [[Kentucky]] and [[Oregon]]. After graduating from [[Stanford University]], he launched Nvidia in 1993 from a local [[Denny's]] restaurant at the age of 30 and has remained president and CEO since its founding. Huang led the company out of near-bankruptcy during the 1990s and oversaw its expansion into [[GPU]] production, [[high-performance computing]], and [[artificial intelligence]]. 

Under Huang, Nvidia experienced rapid growth during the [[AI boom]] and reached a [[Trillion dollar company|market capitalization of $3 trillion]], surpassing [[Microsoft]], [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], and [[Meta Platforms|Meta]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kim |first=Tae |date=November 14, 2024 |title=How Jensen Huang Built Nvidia Into the $3 Trillion King of AI: Nvidia's CEO turned a struggling upstart into the world's most valuable company. It took 30 years. |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/ai-nvidia-jensen-huang-98f40bd3 |access-date=2024-12-23 |website=[[Barron's]] |language=en-US}}</ref> In June 2024, Nvidia overtook Microsoft to be the "world's most valuable company" with a [[market capitalization]] of $3.34 trillion.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Wodecki |first=Ben |date=June 19, 2024 |title=Nvidia Becomes Most Valuable Company in the World, Overtakes Microsoft |url=https://aibusiness.com/companies/nvidia-becomes-most-valuable-company-in-the-world-overtakes-microsoft |work=AI Business}}</ref> In 2021 and 2024, [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] magazine named Huang as [[Time 100|one of the most influential people in the world.]]

== Early life and education <!--Note: Some of these citations apply also to other sentences in their respective paragraph, especially preceding ones.--> ==
Huang was born in [[Taipei]], Taiwan, on February 17, 1963,{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=17}} and moved to the southern city of [[Tainan]] as a child.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Chang |first=Michelle Toh, Wayne |date=2023-11-04 |title=The Taiwanese American cousins going head-to-head in the global AI race |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2023/11/05/tech/nvidia-amd-ceos-taiwan-intl-hnk/index.html |access-date=2024-12-23 |website= |publisher=[[CNN Business]] |language=en}}</ref> He is the younger of two sons of Huang Hsing-tai, a [[chemical engineer]] at an [[oil refinery]], and Lo Tsai-hsiu, a schoolteacher.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Volle |first=Adam |date=December 2024 |title=Jensen Huang: Taiwan-born American entrepreneur |url=https://www.britannica.com/money/Jensen-Huang |access-date=December 15, 2024 |website=[[Encyclopedia Britannica]]}}</ref> They were a middle-class Taiwanese family that relocated often.{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=17}} Each day, Jensen's mother randomly selected ten words from the dictionary to teach her sons English.{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=17–18}} When he was five years old, Huang's family moved to Thailand to support his father's refinery work and remained there for approximately four years.<ref name="Lin" /><ref name=":2" /> He attended [[Ruamrudee International School]] while in [[Bangkok]].<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vN-JDNbiXIc |title=Mr. Jensen Huang ประธานกรรมการบริหารและผู้ก่อตั้งบริษัท NVIDIA เข้าพบนายกรัฐมนตรี |date=2024-12-02 |last=ไทยคู่ฟ้า ทําเนียบรัฐบาล |access-date=2024-12-04 |via=YouTube}} (At 0:27.) This is a video released by the [[Government of Thailand]] of a conversation between Huang and [[Paetongtarn Shinawatra]], the current [[Prime Minister of Thailand]], in which Huang mentions that he was raised in Bangkok and attended the Ruamrudee school.</ref> 

In the late 1960s, Hsing-tai traveled from Taiwan to [[New York City]] to train under an [[air conditioning]] company and, after returning home, resolved to send his sons to the United States.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gurdus |first=Lizzy |date=2018-05-06 |title=Nvidia CEO: My mom taught me English a 'random 10 words at a time' before we emigrated from Taiwan |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/05/06/nvidia-ceo-my-mom-taught-me-english-a-random-10-words-at-a-time.html |access-date=2024-12-24 |website= |publisher=[[CNBC]] |language=en}}</ref> At age nine, Jensen, despite not being able to speak English, was sent by his parents to live in the US.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bhaimiya |first=Sawdah |date=2024-05-13 |title=Nvidia's CEO was labeled a 'demanding' boss by staff. But experts say you have to be cutthroat |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2024/05/13/nvidias-ceo-was-labeled-a-demanding-boss-by-staff-experts-discuss.html |access-date=2024-12-23 |website= |series=Make It |publisher=[[CNBC]] |language=en}}</ref> He and his older brother moved in 1973 to reside with an uncle in [[Tacoma, Washington]], due to widespread social unrest in Thailand.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=Yip |first=Huileng Tan, Lakshmi Varanasi, Theron Mohamed, Beatrice Nolan, Jaures |date=November 6, 2024 |title=Jensen Huang is billions richer as Nvidia overtakes Apple to become world's most valuable company |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/nvidia-jensen-huang-chipmaker-cofounder-ceo-wealth-net-worth-ai-2023-5 |access-date=2024-12-23 |website=[[Business Insider]] |language=en-US}}</ref> Both Huang's aunt and uncle were recent immigrants to [[Washington (state)|Washington]] state; they accidentally enrolled him and his brother in the [[Oneida Baptist Institute]], a religious reform academy in [[Kentucky]] for troubled youth,<ref name=":3" /> mistakenly believing it to be a prestigious boarding school.<ref name="Witt">{{cite magazine |last1=Witt |first1=Stephen |date=November 27, 2023 |title=How Jensen Huang's Nvidia Is Powering the A.I. Revolution |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2023/12/04/how-jensen-huangs-nvidia-is-powering-the-ai-revolution |url-status=live |archive-url=https://archive.today/20231127154917/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2023/12/04/how-jensen-huangs-nvidia-is-powering-the-ai-revolution |archive-date=November 27, 2023 |access-date=December 5, 2023 |magazine=[[The New Yorker]]}}</ref> Jensen's parents sold nearly all their possessions in order to afford the academy's tuition.{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=18}}

When he was ten years old, Huang lived with his brother in the Oneida boys' dormitory.<ref name="Witt" /> Each student was expected to work everyday, and his older brother was assigned to perform manual labor on a nearby [[tobacco farm]].{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=18}} Because he was too young to attend classes at the reform academy, Huang was educated at a separate public school—the Oneida Elementary school in [[Oneida, Kentucky]]—arriving as "an undersized Asian immigrant with long hair and heavily accented English"<ref name="Witt" /> and was frequently bullied and beaten.{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=18–19}} In Oneida, Huang cleaned toilets everyday, learned to play [[Table tennis|table-tennis]],{{Refn|According to ''[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]'', Huang "placed third in junior doubles at the U.S. Table Tennis Open championship, at age 15" in 1978.<ref name="Tilley">{{cite news |last1=Tilley |first1=Aaron |date=November 30, 2016 |title=The New Intel: How Nvidia Went From Powering Video Games To Revolutionizing Artificial Intelligence |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/aarontilley/2016/11/30/nvidia-deep-learning-ai-intel/?sh=6c0e3f037ff1 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230314141243/https://www.forbes.com/sites/aarontilley/2016/11/30/nvidia-deep-learning-ai-intel/?sh=6c0e3f037ff1 |archive-date=March 14, 2023 |access-date=March 14, 2023 |work=Forbes}} </ref>|group=lower-alpha}} joined the swimming team,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Henn |first=Steve |date=February 20, 2012 |title=Tech Pioneer Channels Hard Lessons Into Silicon Valley Success |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/alltechconsidered/2012/02/20/147162496/tech-pioneer-channels-hard-lessons-into-silicon-valley-success |access-date=23 December 2024 |publisher=[[NPR]]}}</ref> and appeared in ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' at age 14.<ref name=":4">{{Cite magazine |author=WIRED Staff |date=July 2002 |title=Meet Nvidia CEO Jen-Hsun Huang, the man who plans to make the CPU obsolete. |url=https://www.wired.com/2002/07/nvidia/ |access-date=2024-12-23 |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |language=en-US |issn=1059-1028}}</ref> He taught his illiterate roommate, a "17-year-old covered in tattoos and knife scars,"<ref name=":4" /> how to read in exchange for being taught how to [[bench press]].<ref name="Witt" /> In 2002, Huang recalled that he remembered his life in Kentucky "more vividly than just about any other".<ref name=":4" />

Two years after Huang arrived in Oneida, his parents moved to the United States and settled in [[Beaverton, Oregon]], where the brothers withdrew from school in Kentucky to live back with them.{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=19}} As a teenager, Huang attended [[Aloha High School]] in [[Aloha, Oregon]],<ref>{{Cite web |last=Parvini |first=Sarah |date=2024-06-21 |title=Nvidia's riding high on AI, and it's not by accident |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/silicon-forest/2024/06/nvidias-riding-high-on-ai-and-its-not-by-accident.html |access-date=2024-12-23 |website=[[The Oregonian]] |language=en}}</ref> where he excelled academically. He [[Grade skipping|skipped]] two grades, graduated at age sixteen, and became a nationally ranked table-tennis player in addition to being a member of its mathematics, computer, and science clubs.<ref name="Witt" /> Beginning at age 15,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lake |first=Sydney |date=March 12, 2024 |title=How Nvidia's billionaire CEO went from Denny's dishwasher to leading a company with a $2 trillion market cap |url=https://fortune.com/2024/03/12/billionaire-nvidia-ceo-first-job-dennys/ |access-date=2024-12-24 |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |language=en}}</ref> Huang also got his first job working the [[graveyard shift]]<ref name=":5">{{Cite web |last=Rogoway |first=Mike |date=2008-06-01 |title=NVIDIA's CEO & his Oregon roots |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/siliconforest/2008/06/nvidias_ceo_has_oregon_roots.html |access-date=2024-12-23 |website=[[The Oregonian]] |language=en}}</ref> at a local [[Denny's]] restaurant as a dishwasher, [[busboy]], and waiter from 1978 to 1983.<ref name=":6">{{Cite web |last=Berger |first=Chloe |date=August 28, 2024 |title=Nvidia's billionaire boss: 'I used to clean bathrooms, and now I'm the CEO' |url=https://fortune.com/2024/08/28/nvidias-billionaire-boss-i-used-to-clean-bathrooms-and-now-im-the-ceo/ |access-date=2024-12-23 |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":7">{{Cite web |last=Anand |first=Nisha |date=August 28, 2024 |title=Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang's experience as 'dishwasher' goes viral on LinkedIn |url=https://www.business-standard.com/companies/people/nvidia-ceo-jensen-huang-s-experience-as-dishwasher-goes-viral-on-linkedin-124082800279_1.html |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20241007210849/https://www.business-standard.com/companies/people/nvidia-ceo-jensen-huang-s-experience-as-dishwasher-goes-viral-on-linkedin-124082800279_1.html |archive-date=2024-10-07 |access-date=2024-12-24 |website=[[Business Standard]] |language=en-US}}</ref>

After high school, Huang chose to enroll in [[Oregon State University]] due to its low [[in-state tuition]].{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=21}} He studied [[electrical engineering]] and [[computer science]] and graduated with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in 1984 at age 20.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-10-03 |title=Jen-Hsun Huang: Engineering Hall of Fame - 2013 {{!}} College of Engineering |url=https://engineering.oregonstate.edu/alumni-partners/oregon-stater-awards/searchable-awards-database/jen-hsun-huang-engineering-hall |access-date=2024-12-23 |website= |publisher=[[Oregon State University]] |language=en}}</ref> He later recalled, "I was the youngest kid in school, in class" and the only student who "looked like a child".<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lee |first=Lakshmi Varanasi, Lloyd |date=November 24, 2024 |title=Here's how Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang won over his wife |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/nvidia-ceo-jensen-huang-how-he-met-his-wife-lori-2024-11 |access-date=2024-12-24 |website=[[Business Insider]] |language=en-US}}</ref> Years later, while working as a microchip designer in [[Silicon Valley]], he concurrently pursued graduate [[night classes]] at [[Stanford University]], where he earned a master's degree in electrical engineering in 1992.<ref name="Witt" /><ref>{{Cite web|date=April 30, 2008|title=#61 Jen-Hsun Huang|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2008/12/lead_bestbosses08_Jen-Hsun-Huang_BAN9.html|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509095920/https://www.forbes.com/lists/2008/12/lead_bestbosses08_Jen-Hsun-Huang_BAN9.html|archive-date=May 9, 2008|access-date=November 15, 2021|website=Forbes|language=en}}</ref>

== AMD and LSI Logic ==
After graduating from college, Huang was a microchip designer in Silicon Valley.<ref name="Witt" /> He had interviewed for positions at [[Texas Instruments]], [[Advanced Micro Devices]] (AMD), and [[LSI Logic]], ultimately choosing the California-based AMD due to already being familiar with the company. He designed AMD [[microprocessor|microprocessors]] while simultaneously attending Stanford and raising his two children. However, when he heard of new chip design processes at LSI Logic, Huang left AMD to assume a role as a technical officer at the LSI Corporation, working under a [[startup company]], [[Sun Microsystems]], where he met engineers [[Chris Malachowsky]] and [[Curtis Priem]].{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=22–23}}

LSI was in contract with Sun Microsystems and had introduced Huang to Malachowsky and Priem, who were working on a new [[graphics accelerator card]]. While the three produced the card's manufacturing process, the relationship between Malachowsky and Priem became strained as the two disputed the chip's design, leading to infighting; according to Malachowsky, they "broke every tool that LSI Logic had in their standard portfolio".{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=33–34}} In 1989, Huang, Malachowsky, and Priem finalized the accelerator, which they called the "GX graphics engine".{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=34}} GX was a widespread financial success; the sales of the graphics engine contributed to Sun Microsystem's revenue increasing from $262 million in 1987 to $656 million in 1990, and Huang was promoted to be the director of LSI's CoreWare, a division that manufactured chips for hardware vendors.{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=36–37}}

== Nvidia <!--Note: Some of these citations apply also to other sentences in their respective paragraph, especially preceding ones.--> ==

=== Founding (1993) ===
[[File:2484 Berryessa Road.jpg|thumb|Huang founded Nvidia Corporation after meeting with [[Chris Malachowsky]] and [[Curtis Priem]] in a [[Denny's]] diner in [[East San Jose]] (pictured). As a teenager, Huang was previously an employee at a Denny's restaurant in Oregon.]]
When business began to slow for Sun Microsystems after 1990, Huang, along with Priem and Malachowsky, each resigned their jobs to pursue a venture together in making [[graphics chips]] for [[PC game|PC games]].{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=39–43}} They initially named their new company "NVision" until Huang suggested that the company be named "Nvidia" based on the Latin word [[Invidia|''invidia'']], as Priem wanted competitors to turn "green with envy".<ref name="Witt" /> The three met frequently in 1992 at a Denny's roadside diner in [[East San Jose]] to formulate a [[business plan]].{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=41}} Huang chose for them to meet at Denny's due to his prior work experience at the restaurant chain and because it was "quieter than home and had cheap coffee".<ref name="Witt" /> The three founded the company during one meeting at the Denny's diner at a breakfast booth.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Jackson |first=Ashton |date=2024-11-05 |title=Nvidia briefly overtakes Apple as world's most valuable company—it began in a breakfast booth at Denny's |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2024/11/05/nvidia-briefly-overtakes-apple-as-most-valuable-us-company-origin-story.html |access-date=2024-12-25 |website= |publisher=[[CNBC]] |language=en}}</ref><ref name="Whitaker">{{cite news |last1=Whitaker |first1=Bill |date=April 28, 2024 |title=Meet Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang, the man behind the $2 trillion company powering today's artificial intelligence |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/meet-nvida-ceo-jensen-huang-company-powering-ai-today-60-minutes-transcript/ |access-date=June 19, 2024 |work=[[60 Minutes]] |publisher=[[CBS News]] |authorlink1=Bill Whitaker (journalist)}}</ref> 

To formally incorporate the company, Huang found a lawyer, James Gaither of [[Cooley LLP|Cooley Godward]], who demanded the $200 in cash in Huang's pockets to capitalize the company.  After that meeting, Huang went back to Priem and Malachowsky to ask each of them for $200 for their respective shares of the company, which meant that Nvidia's initial capital was $600.{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=46–47}}  On April 5, 1993, Huang personally signed Nvidia's original [[articles of incorporation]] into effect.<ref name="NVIDIA_Articles" /> 

Although he left LSI, Huang remained in good standing with the company and was able to secure funding for Nvidia from LSI's CEO, [[Wilfred Corrigan]], who introduced Huang to venture capitalist [[Don Valentine]]. Valentine, the leader of [[Sequoia Capital]], chose to invest in Nvidia, as did [[Sutter Hill Ventures]]. The funding enabled Nvidia to begin development efforts toward its first chip and to begin paying wages for its employees.{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=47–52, 54}} By the first day of operation, Huang was made Nvidia's president and CEO.{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=54–55}} Even though Huang, at age 30, was younger than Priem and Malachowsky, both Priem and Malachowsky believed that he was prepared to be CEO.<ref name="Witt" /> According to Priem, "we basically deferred to Jensen on day one" and told Huang, "you're in charge of running the company—all the stuff Chris and I don’t know how to do".{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=55}}{{Refn|In a 2011 interview at [[Stanford University]], Huang recalled that Priem said, "Jensen, you’re the CEO, right? Done".{{Sfn|Kim|2024a|p=55}}|group=lower-alpha}}

=== President and CEO (1993–) ===


As of 2024, Huang has been Nvidia's chief executive for over three decades, a tenure described by [[The Wall Street Journal|''The Wall Street Journal'']] as "almost unheard of in fast-moving [[Silicon Valley]]".<ref name="fitch20240226">{{Cite news |last=Fitch |first=Asa |date=February 26, 2024 |title=Nvidia's Stunning Ascent Has Also Made It a Giant Target |url=https://www.wsj.com/tech/ai/nvidia-ceo-jensen-huang-vision-company-f05db212 |url-access=subscription |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240227004315/https://www.wsj.com/tech/ai/nvidia-ceo-jensen-huang-vision-company-f05db212 |archive-date=February 27, 2024 |access-date=February 27, 2024 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |language=en-US}}</ref> He owns 3.6% of Nvidia's stock, which went public in 1999.<ref name="Forbes" /> He earned {{USD|24.6 million|link=no}} as CEO in 2007, ranking him as the 61st highest paid U.S. CEO by ''[[Forbes]]''.<ref name="Forbes" />[[File:Jensen_Huang_meeting_with_Indian_PM_Narendra_Modi_02.jpg|thumb|Huang meeting with [[Narendra Modi]] in 2023]]According to Huang, the three co-founders in 1993 had "no idea how" to start a company,<ref name="Whitaker" /> "building Nvidia turned out to have been a million times harder" than they expected, and they probably would not have done it if they had realized up front "the pain and suffering [involved] ... the challenges [they were] going to endure, the embarrassment and the shame, and the list of all the things that [would] go wrong."<ref name="Taylor">{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Chloe |title=Nvidia cofounder Jensen Huang says 'nobody in their right mind' would start a company, and he'd opt out if he could go back in time |url=https://fortune.com/2023/10/23/nvidia-ceo-jensen-huang-tech-startup-entrepreneur/ |access-date=June 19, 2024 |work=Fortune |date=October 23, 2023 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>  For its first graphics accelerator chips, Nvidia focused on rendering [[quadrilateral]] [[Geometric primitive|primitives]] ([[forward texture mapping]]) instead of the triangle primitives preferred by its competitors,<ref name="Witt" /> and barely survived long enough to successfully pivot to triangles only because [[Sega]] agreed to keep Nvidia alive with a $5 million investment.<ref name="Cohen">{{Cite news |last=Cohen |first=Ben |date=May 18, 2024 |title=The 84-Year-Old Man Who Saved Nvidia |url=https://www.wsj.com/business/nvidia-stock-jensen-huang-sega-irimajiri-chips-ai-906247db |work=The Wall Street Journal |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://archive.today/20240518101129/https://www.wsj.com/business/nvidia-stock-jensen-huang-sega-irimajiri-chips-ai-906247db |archive-date=May 18, 2024 |url-status=live}}</ref> By the time the [[RIVA 128]] was released in August 1997 and saved the company, Nvidia was down to one month of payroll.<ref name="Witt" /> This resulted in the "unofficial company motto": "Our company is thirty days from going out of business."<ref name="Witt" /> Huang regularly began presentations to Nvidia staff with those words for many years.<ref name="Witt" />  However, Huang regards the "pain and suffering" of Nvidia's early years as essential to the company's success in later years, because it forced him to become a better leader.<ref name="Huddleston">{{cite news |last1=Huddleston Jr. |first1=Tom |title=Success requires 'ample doses of pain,' billionaire Nvidia CEO tells Stanford students: 'I hope suffering happens to you' |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2024/03/15/nvidia-ceo-huang-at-stanford-pain-and-suffering-breeds-success.html |access-date=June 19, 2024 |work=CNBC Make It |date=March 15, 2024}}</ref>

Huang does not keep a fixed office; he roams Nvidia's headquarters and settles temporarily in conference rooms as needed.<ref name="Nusca">{{cite web |last=Nusca |first=Andrew |date=November 16, 2017 |title=This Man Is Leading an AI Revolution in Silicon Valley—And He's Just Getting Started |url=http://fortune.com/2017/11/16/nvidia-ceo-jensen-huang/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116192021/http://fortune.com/2017/11/16/nvidia-ceo-jensen-huang/ |archive-date=November 16, 2017 |access-date=November 14, 2021 |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |url-access=subscription}}</ref>  He prefers to maintain a relatively flat management structure, with around 60 direct reports as of November 2024,<ref name="Kahn">{{cite news |last1=Kahn |first1=Jeremy |title=60 direct reports, but no 1-on-1 meetings: How an unconventional leadership style helped Jensen Huang of Nvidia become one of the most powerful people in business |url=https://fortune.com/2024/11/12/jensen-huang-nvidia-ceo-leadership-mpp/ |access-date=November 16, 2024 |work=Fortune |date=November 12, 2024 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> on the ground that people reporting directly to him "should be at the top of their game" and "require the least amount of pampering".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leswing |first1=Kit |title=Nvidia CEO: Senior executives don't need pampering, career guidance |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2023/11/29/nvidia-ceo-senior-executives-dont-need-pampering-career-guidance.html |access-date=June 19, 2024 |work=CNBC |date=November 29, 2023}}</ref>  He does not wear a watch, because as he likes to say, "now is the most important time".<ref name="fitch20240226" />

Historically, Huang and Nvidia were well-known only among the [[gamer]]s and [[computer graphics]] experts who were the original intended markets for Nvidia's [[graphics processing unit]] (GPU) products.  In 2017, a ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' profile article acknowledged: "If you haven’t heard of Nvidia, you can be forgiven."<ref name="Nusca" /> During the [[AI boom]], Huang's net worth rose rapidly along with the value of Nvidia's stock, from {{USD|3 billion|link=no}} in 2019 to {{USD|90 billion|link=no}} in May 2024.<ref name="Leswing">{{cite news |last1=Leswing |first1=Kif |title=Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang's net worth swells from $3 billion to $90 billion in five years |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2024/05/24/nvidia-ceo-jensen-huangs-net-worth-swells-by-87-billion-in-5-years.html |access-date=May 30, 2024 |work=CNBC |date=May 24, 2024}}</ref>  During this same timeframe, Huang became more widely known.  In March 2024, [[Mark Zuckerberg]] wrote on [[Instagram]] with a picture of himself and Huang wearing each other's signature jacket: "He's like [[Taylor Swift]], but for tech".<ref name="Tan">{{cite news |last1=Tan |first1=Kwan Wei Kevin |title=Mark Zuckerberg says Nvidia CEO Jensen Huang is basically the Taylor Swift of tech |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/mark-zuckerberg-says-nvidias-jensen-huang-tech-taylor-swift-2024-3 |access-date=June 15, 2024 |work=Business Insider |date=March 27, 2024 |url-access=registration}}</ref>

In June 2024, Nvidia's market capitalization reached {{USD|3 trillion|link=no}} for the first time and Huang's net worth grew to {{USD|100 billion|link=no}}.<ref name="Savov">{{cite news |last1=Savov |first1=Vlad |last2=Lee |first2=Jane Lanhee |last3=Mochizuki |first3=Takashi |title=Nvidia's Rise to $3 Trillion Fuels 'Jensanity' in Tech World |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-06-06/nvidia-s-rise-to-3-trillion-fuels-jensanity-across-tech-world |access-date=June 6, 2024 |work=Bloomberg |date=June 6, 2024| url-access=subscription}}</ref> By then, the news media was using the term "Jensanity" to refer to Huang's celebrity status in Taiwan,<ref name="Savov" /> and it was compared to the [[Jeremy Lin|"Linsanity"]] phenomenon of 2012.<ref name="Lin">{{cite news |last1=Lin |first1=Liza |last2=Wang |first2=Joyu |last3=Jie |first3=Yang |date=June 8, 2024 |title=Nvidia's Jensen Huang Finds Celebrity Status |url=https://www.wsj.com/world/asia/jensen-huang-nvidia-ceo-taiwan-fame-99630726 |url-access=subscription |access-date=June 8, 2024 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> Huang was the center of attention at [[Computex]] 2024 in Taipei, even though he was not on the official speaking program.<ref name="Savov" /> Large crowds of fans and paparazzi followed Huang and his family members around every time they appeared in public during their 2024 visit to Taiwan.<ref name="Savov" /><ref name="Lin" />

=== Philanthropy ===
In 2008, Nvidia contributed funds to establish a classroom at the [[Beijing Haidian Foreign Language Shi Yan School]] to cater to 101 elementary and middle school students from regions affected by the [[2008 Wenchuan earthquake]] in China. As a gesture of appreciation for the donation, the students ceremoniously bestowed a [[red scarf]] upon Huang, symbolizing their gratitude towards him. In return, Huang gifted kaleidoscopes to the students as a gesture of appreciation during the donation ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://vga.zol.com.cn/102/1024978.html|title=中国情 灾区学生亲手为黄仁勋系红领巾|first=Bo|last=Liu|newspaper=ZOL|date=June 8, 2008|access-date=June 7, 2024}}</ref> In addition, Huang also provided a donation of {{USD|30 million|link=no}} to his former university, Stanford University, in order to establish the Jen-Hsun Huang School of Engineering Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news-service.stanford.edu/news/2008/september10/building-091008.html|title=Alumnus, NVIDIA founder pledges $30 million for campus engineering center|work=Stanford University|access-date=August 6, 2015|archive-date=September 22, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090922193403/http://news-service.stanford.edu/news/2008/september10/building-091008.html|url-status=live}}</ref> The building is the second of four that make up Stanford's Science and Engineering Quad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://engineering.stanford.edu/visit/buildings/jen-hsun-huang-engineering-center |title=Jen-Hsun Huang Engineering Center |access-date=August 6, 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905133614/http://engineering.stanford.edu/visit/buildings/jen-hsun-huang-engineering-center |archive-date=September 5, 2015}}</ref>

In 2019, Huang donated $2 million to his former school, [[Oneida Baptist Institute]], for the construction of Huang Hall, a modern facility that serves as a dormitory and classroom building for female students.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Events and News: Jen-Hsun Huang Hall Dedication Ceremony |url=https://www.oneidaschool.org/newsevents.shtml |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220330053443/https://www.oneidaschool.org/newsevents.shtml |archive-date=March 30, 2022 |access-date=November 15, 2021 |website=Oneida Baptist Institute}}</ref>

In 2022, Huang gifted {{USD|50 million|link=no}} to his alma mater, [[Oregon State University]], as part of a larger {{USD|200 million|link=no}} philanthropic contribution to establish a cutting-edge supercomputing institute on the university campus.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rogoway |first=Mike |date=October 15, 2022 |title=OSU plans $200m supercomputer center backed by $50m from Nvidia CEO |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/silicon-forest/2022/10/oregon-state-plans-200-million-supercomputer-center-backed-by-50-million-from-nvidia-ceo.html |access-date=October 15, 2022 |website=[[OregonLive.com]] |language=en |archive-date=October 15, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221015202805/https://www.oregonlive.com/silicon-forest/2022/10/oregon-state-plans-200-million-supercomputer-center-backed-by-50-million-from-nvidia-ceo.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

